{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:18:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:18:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19036"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19036"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.48,0.07,0.32,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11770"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85309"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3730"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy is admitted to hospital with febrile neutropenia during chemotherapy for acute lymphoblastic leukaemia. He has no other medical conditions. His current medications include methotrexate, vincristine, gentamicin, vancomycin, and regular paracetamol. He has been receiving intravenous fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn day four of admission, he appears lethargic. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His urine output has decreased to 0.5 mL/kg/hour over the past eight hours. Blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine 120 \u00b5mol/L (30-60)\u003Cbr /\u003ESerum urea 15.0 mmol/L (2.5-6.5)\u003Cbr /\u003ESerum potassium 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ESerum sodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his acute kidney injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Post-renal obstruction","Multiple nephrotoxic medications","Interstitial nephritis","Tumour lysis syndrome","Pre-renal acute kidney injury"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with acute kidney injury (AKI) as evidenced by rising creatinine and reduced urine output. While there are several potential causes in this complex patient, the combination of multiple nephrotoxic medications is the most likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple nephrotoxic medications\u003C/strong\u003E including gentamicin, vancomycin, methotrexate, and regular paracetamol can cause cumulative damage to the kidneys. The risk is particularly high when these medications are used in combination. Aminoglycosides and vancomycin can cause direct tubular toxicity, while methotrexate can cause crystal nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour lysis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs at the initiation of chemotherapy and presents with more severe electrolyte derangements including hyperuricemia, hyperphosphataemia, and hyperkalaemia. The timing and biochemistry do not fit with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-renal acute kidney injury\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the patient is receiving intravenous fluids and does not have significant hypotension or signs of dehydration. The blood pressure, while at the lower end of normal, is appropriate for his age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-renal obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely without symptoms of urinary obstruction or imaging findings suggesting this. While patients with malignancy can develop obstructive uropathy, there are no features suggesting this here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, rash, and eosinophilia. While it can be caused by medications, the presentation here is more consistent with direct nephrotoxicity rather than an allergic mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement would include reviewing and stopping non-essential nephrotoxic medications, ensuring adequate hydration, and close monitoring of fluid balance and renal function. Drug levels should be monitored where appropriate, and doses adjusted according to renal function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple nephrotoxic medications increase the risk of acute kidney injury in children.","Regular monitoring of renal function is essential when prescribing potentially nephrotoxic medications.","Early recognition and cessation of nephrotoxic medications is crucial in managing medication-induced acute kidney injury."],"references":["Sethi SK, Bunchman T, Chakraborty R, Raina R. Pediatric acute kidney injury: new advances in the last decade. Kidney Res Clin Pract. 2021 Mar;40(1):40-51. doi: 10.23876/j.krcp.20.074. Epub 2021 Mar 3. PMID: 33663033; PMCID: PMC8041642."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85309"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19036"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85309"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-16T13:51:55+09:30","upda